Comment: This is my second annotation. This game was interesting and a game I was happy to win. I always like to move my king's pawn two spaces.
A response move I am not that familiar with, but I had to go on anyway.
I stop the pawn moving by moving Bc4 and also attacking f7.
flyfish283's knight comes into play.
My queen could checkmate on the next move, by moving Qf3.
The attack is blocked with Nf6. I wasn't expecting a win that easy anyway. Not many people win in four moves.
So my knight opens the other way with Nh3.
flyfish283's pawn advances two spaces to e5.
My knight becomes more attacking, and if the opponent is not careful, they could be down ten points.
The bishop comes out, but that doesn't stop me from going Nxf7.
I am now attacking flyfish283's queen and rook and is being protected by my bishop. flyfish283 obviously moves his queen out of the way allowing me to take the rook.
The queen moves away to a5.
I take the rook.
Nd4 opens an attack on my queen, so I move it quickly.
The queen's pawn comes down to attack my pawn and bishop.
The queen's pawn comes down to attack my pawn and bishop.
I really should have taken it with my pawn, but this is more attacking.
I get taken, but I take his knight by exd5.
Seven points up in a tournament game gives me good self-esteem and motivation to keep going.
Bf5 was a smart move. Why did I castle?
Nxc2 lost me my rook, so I needed to regain those lost points.
Nxc2 lost me my rook, so I needed to regain those lost points.
